{"key":"post-12725119","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12725119</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The intention of the rice bran is too be a cheap alterniative to brown rice flour.&lt;br /&gt;I understand also that rice bran is an additive that can be used for your coir&lt;br /&gt;substrates. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I'd strongly discourage using rice bran in a coir substrate unless you're going to sterilize and colonize the coir in a filter patch bag.&amp;nbsp; Don't use rice bran, or any other bran or brf in any substrate that is going to colonize while exposed to air.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Being cheaper is only one reason to use rice bran.&amp;nbsp; Brans are more nutritious than flours because the outer husk is left on when ground.&amp;nbsp; Otherwise, it's the same product as brown rice flour.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Be wary of people who get all arrogant based on only one grow.&amp;nbsp; I've used rice bran on thousands of grows over the years, and it's a great product.&amp;nbsp; If you're growing from spores, ensure that the brand you buy isn't treated with fungicides.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A small amount of calcium carbonate such as they add to the horse feed supplement is fine.&amp;nbsp; I doubt they add enough to effect the pH much.&amp;nbsp; They're adding the calcium as a supplement for bone health in animals, but fungi also needs calcium, and mushrooms are one of our best sources of dietary calcium.&amp;nbsp; It's the reason we use gypsum.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12726801</next>\n<prev>12724580</prev>\n<first>12714294</first>\n<last>22552227</last>\n<when>1276266598</when>\n<utime>06/11/10 05:29 PM</utime>\n</post>"}